caption: I had a really unpleasant visit here tonight. I was on a first date so it was already awkward, there was a laundry list of rules spouted off at us by the host when checking in. There was no way I was going to be able to take it all in, being ADHD and having auditory processing disorder, it’s hard to take in a lot of information given to me verbally. I would recommend making a small sign with all these rules to put somewhere visible at the check in (maybe there was and I missed it... I was a little turned around because the restaurant was hard to find in the alley).  The waitress was flat out rude. I did not catch that there was a rule that you needed to put your mask back on when a staff member approached your table. It was so awkward, the first time she just stood several feet away from our table glaring at me till my date had to tell me to put my mask on. The next time she approached from behind and was clearly p i s s e d. I got reprimanded “I’m going to need to remind you to put your mask on when I approach.” Being that she came from behind, I did not see her approaching. I put it on as soon as I saw her and was informed you have to put your mask back on when actively eating or drinking. The first time she approached us I understood why I needed to put it back on because we didn’t have any food or water yet, but the second time I thought it was ok since I was in the middle of drinking some thing. Last time I ate out in DC the rule was your mask could be off when seated at a restaurant so I was caught off guard by this rule.  I feel bad leaving a sub par review during the pandemic when restaurants are struggling, but the waitress actively did not hide her disdain for me, it made it so uncomfortable. I know it was freezing and raining, but I just paid $25 for a meatball sub with three meatballs in it and a can of coke, please don’t be so obviously annoyed with me. I get it must be frustrating dealing with people all the time who don’t know that you need to put your mask back on when staff comes to the table, but please be kind to your customers... some of us have also been struggling during the pandemic and don’t get out a ton and don’t know all the rules.  There was another male waiter who was very friendly. The hostess was also super friendly but it did get awkward as she had to check our IDs for contact tracing, I did not know it was my date’s birthday and she made a big deal about it and I felt horrible I didn’t know.  Anyway, I’d recommend better signage both up front and at each table reminding people of the mask rules.

I have always been a fan of Calico and have recommended it to people and even had two of my birthday celebrations there. Unfortunately the last two times I've been there I've been very disappointed with the service/atmosphere. I'm giving 2 stars because all though I appreciate them reopening during a pandemic, the experience was one of the worst dining experiences I've had the last 6 years living in DC. The second to last time I was there, (on my birthday a year ago), there was a massive amount of vomit on the stairway leading up to their patio that smelled horribly and for the hour plus my friends and I were there not a single employee attempted to clean it up.  This last time was during the pandemic and again, good on them for opening, but it was an utterly miserable and unwelcoming experience. I made a reservation days in advance and was running a few minutes late so I called about 5 minutes before my reservation to let them know I'd be a few min late. Half of my party was there on time and the front desk person told my friends that us being a few minutes late was a real burden on them and they had to shift around their seating completely, (why that would be necessary after only a few minutes I have no idea). They ended up seating us in the front next to the check in table and it was in the area below their patio that was on concrete and surrounded by what look like 15 foot walls, (pretty sure this was where their trash cans used to be pre-pandemic so clearly not ideal and it was obvious they decided to put us there instead of the table we were initially slated to get just because we were slightly late). The seating area was miserable and the steps to get drinks/food was even worse. I'm talking QR code, sign up for an account, verify twice I'm not a robot - level upon level of hoops to jump through just to order from them! You even had to request a bathroom visit through the app and a staff member popped around the corner to ask which one of us needed to use the bathroom - awkward. The food/drinks are pricey and I love their juice boxes, but I won't be going back any time soon. If you love them and want to keep them open during this time, I strongly recommend figuring out how to donate to them and avoiding the experience of being there in person!

Nice beer garden with decent finger food, watered down drinks, and prevailing gentrification. I see why Calico is a hit/miss with 3.5 stars and doesn't quite live up to the hype.  While the patio is spacious with a cool birdcage room (luckily enclosed during the winter) and dog-friendly, the subpar food and drinks don't add up to the premium prices.  The crispy Brussel Sprouts were delicious and my favorite app! They were perfectly fried and the eclectic mix of cashews and apples topped with sweet chunky vinaigrette surprisingly paired well with the brussel sprouts.  The creamy Mac & cheese was tasty, but drowning in sauce. Wish there was gouda, cheddar, and a couple of other cheeses blended in. I'm glad I got the Mac over the hummus and some of the other apps.  The crispy Loaded Tots with bacon, scallions, sour cream, and mozzarella cheese were okay. They weren't particularly memorable and least favorite of the 3 apps.  The bourbon-based "Fight Club" was tart, the ginger overpowered the brown sugar. It just wasn't balanced out. The Prosecco was dry and disappointing. It wasn't even served in a wine glass! Teeny tiny glass not  not worth $10. Glad I ventured away from the sugary juice boxes, heeding the warming of my fellow Yelpers. There's much left to be desired for the cocktails.  Note the online menu is outdated featuring the FALL 2018 menu - many apps have changed. The menu changes seasonally, with the new spring menu coming out this week! Sadly, the eggplant parm mozzarella sticks aren't offered or the Hot Cocktails.  Best part? Service was great - tots were on the house as the server forgot to put them in. I honestly felt bad for the servers, dealing with soo many impatient entitled folks.  The outdoor area gets packed over the weekends - so be prepared to hunt around. I had to scour like a hawk and stake my claim!  Despite the nice outdoor space, the gentrification and lack of diversity was a deterrent from the ambiance. Sweeping the crowds and the tables next to us, there wasn't a pop of color here. Not sure if I have a reason to be back.

This review is going to be on the hiring process since they don’t have a glassdoor available:  I was offered a position back in March by the hiring manager and was dropped the next day mid-training because I couldn’t fulfill the hours they wanted me to work (public transportation/metro times).  After getting fired, I explained to the hiring manager my current financial situation and that they would have to file some information to prove what happened or I would lose my unemployment income.  Fast forward to this week, I saw the same hiring manager and they offered me an interview, refill out the application and a date to start on Friday. I come in to meet the hiring manager for the paperwork, and the hiring manager themselves weren’t there and had a someone else to fill in for them for that process. It went extremely well and I was hopeful to start my training the next day. A day before my first day of work, the hiring manager called me to rescind my position without any explanation. When I pleaded for a reason behind it, the most they were able to tell me was they had remembered me from March and that decision was final (even though I had reliable transportation now).  I’m not sure what might’ve turned them off about me or my situation (maybe unemployment paperwork? I had to nearly beg for them to tell me how I can change in the future for other employers), but I always offered kindness, honesty, confidence and integrity for the whole couple of hours with the company and all of the staff enjoyed having me on the team.  Other than the hiring manager, the hiring process and trainers were amazing. They were willing to teach me how to serve without any prior experience and I appreciate that extremely.  For someone that needs a job badly and is in a similar position I am in, please take my advice and avoid ...honestly I don’t even know how to give advice on this other than have backups available and don’t tell them you’re receiving unemployment?

If you want a chill, yet still regal night out, head to Calico and bring your phone as you'll want to document it all on social media. Here's why:  1) The location- It's in historic Blagden Alley, one of the coolest spots in all of Washington, DC. There are murals nearby and the bricks covering the alley alone make this a great place to photograph.  2) The set up- inside and out is set up like a fancy dining hall. The bar is so big there's seating inside AND outside. Outside are several wooden patios including one with a beautiful steel cage around it perfectly lit.  3) The food- the tomato pie is to die for as is the mac and cheese. What's not to die for are the roasted squash. It wasn't fully cooked and not so tasty.  4) The drinks- two words- adult juice pouches. They make their own cocktails in a sizeable juice pouch and it's perfect!  If you want a place to host a large group for a birthday, this is one of the best options in the city!
There needs to be more people hear spread the word! #Calico #Backyardbar

This new Blagden Alley spot has a fun mod meets granny chic (peep the flowered lighting over the bar) meets rustic decor with a good size space for groups in the back garden and space for singles and pairs at the indoor/outdoor 360 degree bar.  Loved the local beer, wine, and liquor happy hour, hope the options will expand a bit over time with the producers.  Some of the food was really quite good--the steamed shrimp were some of the best we've had around town and my husband orders them pretty much any place he can find them.  The tomato pie was tasty, but we hope in the future there is an option to add protein to make it more of a meal option.  The part we took home and covered with steak slices was out of this world good. The mac n cheese was tasty but not mind blowing.  For 5$ we were happy with it. The fried clams were a heartbreaker--clearly brought in pre-made and frozen, and drowned in mayo to try to cover it up.  Upside, they were more than happy to take the clams off the check and either legitimately interested in customer feedback or fantastic at pretending (we were there a week or two after opening and folks came around to ask, in detail, how we liked pretty much everything that hit the table). The service was terrific and friendly all around--bartenders, food runners, managers.  We liked the energy and the crowd--diverse and not too packed on our visit, though I fear if they refine their menu and find their groove, it will get hard to grab a spot.
Looking forward to going to Calico a lot in the future! The bar does have an indoor area in addition to the beautiful patio! Tried many drinks and they were all good
Great food and drinks! Cool spot in Blagden Alley!
